== Congruences ==

Srinivasa Ramanujan is credited with discovering that the partition function has nontrivial patterns in modular arithmetic.
For instance the number of partitions is divisible by five whenever the decimal representation of formula_8 ends in the digit 4 or 9, as expressed by the congruence
formula_37
For instance, the number of partitions for the integer 4 is 5.
For the integer 9, the number of partitions is 30; for 14 there are 135 partitions. This congruence is implied by the more general identity
formula_38
also by Ramanujan, where the notation formula_39 denotes the product defined by
formula_40
A short proof of this result can be obtained from the partition function generating function.

Ramanujan also discovered congruences modulo 7 and 11:
formula_41
The first one comes from Ramanujan&#x27;s identity
formula_42

Since 5, 7, and 11 are consecutive primes, one might think that there would be an analogous congruence for the next prime 13, formula_43 for some . However, there is no congruence of the form formula_44 for any prime &quot;b&quot; other than 5, 7, or 11. Instead, to obtain a congruence, the argument of formula_45 should take the form formula_46 for some formula_47. In the 1960s, A. O. L. Atkin of the University of Illinois at Chicago discovered additional congruences of this form for small prime moduli. For example:
formula_48

 proved that there are such congruences for every prime modulus greater than 3. Later, showed there are partition congruences modulo every integer coprime to 6.

==Approximation formulas==

Approximation formulas exist that are faster to calculate than the exact formula given above.

An asymptotic expression for &quot;p&quot;(&quot;n&quot;) is given by
:formula_49 as formula_50.
This asymptotic formula was first obtained by G. H. Hardy and Ramanujan in 1918 and independently by J. V. Uspensky in 1920. Considering formula_51, the asymptotic formula gives about formula_52, reasonably close to the exact answer given above (1.415% larger than the true value).

Hardy and Ramanujan obtained an asymptotic expansion with this approximation as the first term:
