<doc id="312293" wikidata="Q576478" url="?curid=312293" title="Liouville's theorem (complex analysis)">
<text>In complex analysis, Liouville&#x27;s theorem, named after Joseph Liouville (although the theorem was first proven by Cauchy in 1844), states that every bounded entire function must be constant. That is, every holomorphic function formula_1 for which there exists a positive number formula_2 such that formula_3 for all formula_4 is constant. Equivalently, non-constant holomorphic functions on formula_5 have unbounded images.

The theorem is considerably improved by Picard&#x27;s little theorem, which says that every entire function whose image omits two or more complex numbers must be constant.

== Statement ==
Liouville&#x27;s theorem: Every holomorphic function formula_6 for which there exists a positive number formula_2 such that formula_3 for all formula_4 is constant.

More succinctly, Liouville&#x27;s theorem states that every bounded entire function must be constant.

== Proof ==

This important theorem has several proofs.

A standard analytical proof uses the fact that holomorphic functions are analytic. 

\,d\zeta&lt;/math&gt;

and formula_10 is the circle about 0 of radius formula_11. Suppose formula_1 is bounded: i.e. there exists a constant formula_2 such that formula_14 for all formula_15. We can estimate directly

: formula_16

where in the second inequality we have used the fact that formula_17 on the circle formula_10. (This estimate is known as Cauchy&#x27;s estimate.) But the choice of formula_19 in the above is an arbitrary positive number. Therefore, letting formula_19 tend to infinity (we let formula_19 tend to infinity since formula_1 is analytic on the entire plane) gives formula_23 for all formula_24. Thus formula_25 and this proves the theorem.
Another proof uses the mean value property of harmonic functions.
The proof can be adapted to the case where the harmonic function formula_1 is merely bounded above or below. See Harmonic function#Liouville&#x27;s theorem.

== Corollaries ==

===Fundamental theorem of algebra===
There is a short proof of the fundamental theorem of algebra using Liouville&#x27;s theorem.

===No entire function dominates another entire function===
A consequence of the theorem is that &quot;genuinely different&quot; entire functions cannot dominate each other, i.e. if formula_1 and formula_28 are entire, and formula_29 everywhere, then formula_30 for some complex number formula_31. Consider that for formula_32 the theorem is trivial so we assume formula_33. Consider the function formula_34. It is enough to prove that formula_35 can be extended to an entire function, in which case the result follows by Liouville&#x27;s theorem. The holomorphy of formula_35 is clear except at points in formula_37. But since formula_35 is bounded and all the zeroes of formula_28 are isolated, any singularities must be removable. Thus formula_35 can be extended to an entire bounded function which by Liouville&#x27;s theorem implies it is constant.

===If &quot;f&quot; is less than or equal to a scalar times its input, then it is linear===
Suppose that formula_1 is entire and formula_42, for formula_43. We can apply Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula; we have that

:formula_44

where formula_45 is the value of the remaining integral. This shows that formula_46 is bounded and entire, so it must be constant, by Liouville&#x27;s theorem. Integrating then shows that formula_1 is affine and then, by referring back to the original inequality, we have that the constant term is zero.

===Non-constant elliptic functions cannot be defined on the complex plane===
The theorem can also be used to deduce that the domain of a non-constant elliptic function formula_1 cannot be formula_5. Suppose it was. Then, if formula_50 and formula_51 are two periods of formula_1 such that formula_53 is not real, consider the parallelogram formula_54 whose vertices are 0, formula_50, formula_51, and formula_57. Then the image of formula_1 is equal to formula_59. Since formula_1 is continuous and formula_54 is compact, formula_59 is also compact and, therefore, it is bounded. So, formula_1 is constant.

The fact that the domain of a non-constant elliptic function formula_1 cannot be formula_5 is what Liouville actually proved, in 1847, using the theory of elliptic functions. In fact, it was Cauchy who proved Liouville&#x27;s theorem.

===Entire functions have dense images===
If formula_1 is a non-constant entire function, then its image is dense in formula_5. This might seem to be a much stronger result than Liouville&#x27;s theorem, but it is actually an easy corollary. If the image of formula_1 is not dense, then there is a complex number formula_69 and a real number 
formula_70 such that the open disk centered at formula_69 with radius formula_19 has no element of the image of formula_1. Define 

:formula_74

Then formula_28 is a bounded entire function, since for all formula_15,

:formula_77

So, formula_28 is constant, and therefore formula_1 is constant.

== On compact Riemann surfaces ==
Any holomorphic function on a compact Riemann surface is necessarily constant.

Let formula_80 be holomorphic on a compact Riemann surface formula_2. By compactness, there is a point formula_82 where formula_83 attains its maximum. Then we can find a chart from a neighborhood of formula_84 to the unit disk formula_85 such that formula_86 is holomorphic on the unit disk and has a maximum at formula_87, so it is constant, by the maximum modulus principle.

== Remarks ==

Let formula_88 be the one-point compactification of the complex plane formula_5. In place of holomorphic functions defined on regions in formula_5, one can consider regions in formula_88. Viewed this way, the only possible singularity for entire functions, defined on formula_92, is the point formula_93. If an entire function formula_1 is bounded in a neighborhood of formula_93, then formula_93 is a removable singularity of formula_1, i.e. formula_1 cannot blow up or behave erratically at formula_93. In light of the power series expansion, it is not surprising that Liouville&#x27;s theorem holds.

Similarly, if an entire function has a pole of order formula_100 at formula_93 —that is, it grows in magnitude comparably to formula_102 in some neighborhood of formula_93 
—then formula_1 is a polynomial. This extended version of Liouville&#x27;s theorem can be more precisely stated: if formula_105 for formula_106 sufficiently large, then formula_1 is a polynomial of degree at most formula_100. This can be proved as follows. Again take the Taylor series representation of formula_1,

:formula_110

The argument used during the proof using Cauchy estimates shows that for all formula_111,

:formula_112

So, if formula_113, then

:formula_114

Therefore, formula_115.

Liouville&#x27;s theorem does not extend to the generalizations of complex numbers known as double numbers and dual numbers.

